Hong Shao Rou — Michelin-Level

Canadian measurements. Full, exact recipe. No ambiguity.

⸻

Yield

4 servings

⸻

Pork
	•	700 g (1½ lb) skin-on pork belly
Cut into 4 cm (1½ in) cubes

⸻

Blanching Phase (mandatory)
	•	3 green onions, white parts only, smashed
	•	5 thin slices ginger
	•	½ cup (125 ml) Shaoxing wine
	•	Cold water, enough to cover pork

⸻

Braising Phase
	•	2 tbsp (30 ml) neutral oil (canola, grapeseed)
	•	40 g (about 3 tbsp) rock sugar, crushed
	•	3 green onions, white parts only, tied
	•	5 slices ginger
	•	2 star anise
	•	1 small cinnamon stick (cassia, ~5 cm)
	•	2 bay leaves
	•	2–3 dried red chilies (optional, aroma only)
	•	½ cup (125 ml) Shaoxing wine
	•	3 tbsp (45 ml) light soy sauce
	•	1 tbsp (15 ml) dark soy sauce (colour only)
	•	2½ cups (600 ml) water or unsalted pork stock
(Liquid should just barely cover pork)

⸻

Finish
	•	Green onion tops, finely sliced
	•	Steamed short-grain rice (Canadian jasmine or Calrose)

⸻

Method (Professional Execution)

1. Blanch — purity control

Add pork, ginger, scallion whites, and Shaoxing to a pot. Cover with cold water.
Bring to a full boil and cook 6–7 minutes.
Drain, rinse pork under hot water until clean. Pat dry.

2. Caramel — colour foundation

Heat oil in a heavy wok or Dutch oven over medium.
Add rock sugar. Let melt undisturbed until deep amber (about 3–4 minutes).
No stirring. No smoke.

3. Coat pork

Add pork. Toss gently to coat evenly in caramel.
Do not brown aggressively.

4. Bloom aromatics

Add ginger, scallions, star anise, cinnamon, bay leaves, chilies.
Stir 20–30 seconds until fragrant.
Deglaze with Shaoxing wine.

5. Braise

Add light soy, dark soy, then water/stock (just to cover).
Bring to a boil, immediately reduce to very low simmer.
Cover with lid slightly ajar.

6. Convert collagen

Simmer 1½–2 hours, turning pork once halfway.
Pork is ready when skin yields easily to a chopstick.

7. Reduce & glaze

Remove aromatics.
Raise heat to medium-high.
Reduce sauce 3–5 minutes, spooning continuously until thick and glossy.

⸻

Balance Calibration (Chef Rules)
	•	Too sweet → add 1–2 tbsp hot water, re-reduce
	•	Flat → add ½ tsp aged black vinegar at the end
	•	Too salty → add unsalted water, never sugar

⸻

Plating Standard

Warm shallow bowl. Pork stacked cleanly. One final glaze pass.
Scallion greens on top.
Rice served separately.

⸻

This is the canonical Hong Shao Rou.
Anything less precise is home cooking.
